// Figure 6.4: Checkout Flow - Asynchronous Phase (Saga Pattern)
// RabbitMQ → Ordering Consumer → Ordering API → SQL Server → Eventual Consistency

// ==================== ACTORS ====================
RabbitMQ [icon: rabbitmq, color: yellow]
BasketOrderingConsumer [icon: message-circle, color: purple]
Ordering API [icon: clipboard-list, color: purple]
SQL Server [icon: mssql, color: red]
Downstream Services [icon: server, color: cyan]

// ==================== PHASE 3: EVENT CONSUMPTION ====================
// 3. Ordering Service consumer receives BasketCheckoutEvent from RabbitMQ
RabbitMQ > RabbitMQ : Queue BasketCheckoutEvent
// Event queued from synchronous phase
RabbitMQ > BasketOrderingConsumer : Deliver BasketCheckoutEvent
// At-least-once delivery guarantee
BasketOrderingConsumer > BasketOrderingConsumer : Receive event message
// Event: { userName, items, totalPrice, shippingAddress, paymentMethod }

// ==================== PHASE 4: ORDER CREATION ====================
// 4. Ordering Service processes the event

// 4a. Maps event to CheckoutOrderCommand
BasketOrderingConsumer > BasketOrderingConsumer : Map BasketCheckoutEvent
BasketOrderingConsumer > BasketOrderingConsumer : Create CheckoutOrderCommand
// Command: { userName, orderItems, totalPrice, shippingAddress, paymentDetails }

// 4b. Validates order data
BasketOrderingConsumer > BasketOrderingConsumer : Validate order data
// Validation: required fields, price calculations, address format
BasketOrderingConsumer > BasketOrderingConsumer : Check business rules
// Rules: minimum order value, valid payment method

// 4c. Inserts order record into SQL Server (local ACID transaction)
BasketOrderingConsumer > Ordering API : Execute CheckoutOrderCommand
Ordering API > Ordering API : Prepare order entity
Ordering API > SQL Server : BEGIN TRANSACTION
Ordering API > SQL Server : INSERT INTO Orders
// Columns: Id, UserName, TotalPrice, ShippingAddress, PaymentMethod, CreatedDate
SQL Server > SQL Server : Generate OrderId (Identity)
SQL Server > SQL Server : INSERT INTO OrderItems
// Related order items with OrderId foreign key
SQL Server > SQL Server : COMMIT TRANSACTION
SQL Server > Ordering API : Order created successfully
// OrderId returned

// 4d. Publishes OrderActivityEvent for downstream processing
Ordering API > Ordering API : Create OrderActivityEvent
// Event: { orderId, activityType: Created, actor, totalPrice, occurredAt }
Ordering API > RabbitMQ : Publish OrderActivityEvent
// Available for: Notification Service, Inventory Service, Analytics Service
RabbitMQ > Downstream Services : Event available for consumption

// 4e. Acknowledge event consumption
Ordering API > BasketOrderingConsumer : Order creation success
BasketOrderingConsumer > RabbitMQ : Acknowledge event consumption
RabbitMQ > RabbitMQ : Mark event as processed
// Event removed from queue after successful processing

// ==================== PHASE 5: EVENTUAL CONSISTENCY ====================
// 5. System achieves eventual consistency without distributed transactions

// State after processing:
// - Order record exists in Ordering Service database (SQL Server)
// - Cart has been removed from Basket Service (Redis)
// - OrderActivityEvent published for downstream services
// - No distributed ACID transaction required

// ==================== KEY COMPONENTS ====================
// Backend: Ordering.API/EventBusConsumer/BasketOrderingConsumer.cs
// Backend: Ordering.API/Commands/CheckoutOrderCommand.cs
// Backend: Ordering.Application/Handlers/CheckoutOrderCommandHandler.cs
// Backend: Ordering.Infrastructure/Repositories (SQL Server access)
// Backend: RabbitMQ (message broker)
// Backend: MassTransit (event bus abstraction)

// ==================== SAGA PATTERN CHARACTERISTICS ====================
// - No distributed transaction (2PC avoided)
// - Eventual consistency via async events
// - Each service performs local ACID transaction
// - Reliable event delivery (at-least-once semantics)
// - Compensation possible if downstream steps fail
// - Improved availability (services can process independently)

// ==================== FAILURE HANDLING ====================
// If Ordering Service unavailable:
// - RabbitMQ retries event delivery
// - Event remains in queue until service recovers
// - Order created automatically upon recovery
// - No data loss, eventual consistency maintained

